The conversation delves into the plausibility of a 12-year-old tradesman's son being a voracious reader in 1630, highlighting factors like location, social class, educational opportunities, and access to printed materials. Details on learning to read in the early 17th century are provided, emphasizing home education, apprenticeships, classroom settings, methods of learning, daily routines, community interaction, and access to materials. The discussion offers a nuanced portrayal of how the character's passion for reading could have been nurtured through a combination of informal and formal learning channels, enriching his development in a time of evolving literacy practices.
